<h1>From Major General Artemas Ward</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Boston 11th April 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I am to inform your Excellency that Col. Glover applied to me for a Warrant upon the Paymaster Genl to pay those Men who are in the Service of the Continent, on board the Continental
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0054">[54]</span>
Privateers just arrived from a Cruise, but I did not think myself authorised by your Instructions to grant a Warrant; he informed me the Men would not be induced to go out again unless they received their pay, I therefore directed him to supply the places of such Men as might leave the Privateers, out of his Regiment, until I could receive your Directions in the matter.</p>
<p>The Agent for the Privateers at Beverly, Capt. Bartlett has likewise applyed for the same purpose. I must therefore beg the favour of your particular Directions relative to the above mentioned applications.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I have not been able to collect any material intelligence from the people taken on board the Transport, which Commodore Manley sent into Portsmouth; the general account they give, is, that the Enemy are going to Quebec as soon as the River opens.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>A fifty Gun Ship, with three Transports, lies in Nantasket Road. A Man who made his Escape from the Ship informs that the Officers on board said they were to lie there until the Transports arrived which are expected from Europe and then to follow the Fleet.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> I am Your Excellencys Obedient Humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Artemas Ward</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>: Ward Papers.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>General Wards aide-de-camp Joseph Ward wrote to Col. John Glover on 7 April directing him to furnish the armed vessels with as many men out of your Regiment as may be necessary to man them for a Cruise of a month (if you can do it and have men left sufficient to guard the Stores &amp; Vessels at Beverly) unless General Washington should order otherwise before the month is out (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Bell Clark et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Naval Documents of the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;. 11 vols. to date. Washington, D.C., 1964. ]">Clark and Morgan, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Naval Documents</span></span>, 4:69496). See also Artemas Ward to William Bartlett, 15 April, ibid., 831.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The brigantine <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Elizabeth</span> was captured on 2 April.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0041-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The British warship <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Renown</span> remained at the entrance to Boston Harbor until 14 June when it departed with a convoy of transports for Halifax.</p>

</div>
</div>
